"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1022"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"1989"},{"type":"tags","id":"1993"},{"type":"tags","id":"2451"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"},{"type":"tags","id":"13209"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/974/tags","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/974/relationships/tags"}},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9895"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28402"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41879"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47077"},{"type":"contributions","id":"52947"},{"type":"contributions","id":"53081"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/974/contributions","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/974/relationships/contributions"}}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"119711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/119711"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman, G2P1, presents to the pregnancy assessment unit with lower abdominal cramping at 33 weeks gestation. This pregnancy has been uncomplicated although she has  continued smoking. Her previous pregnancy was significant for preterm birth at 35 weeks. She has no medical history and is on no medications apart from a pregnancy multivitamin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA speculum examination is performed which the cervix is posterior, high and 2cm dilated. Swabs for Group B streptococcus are taken. No amniotic fluid is visible and the Amnicator test is negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be helpful in determining this woman\u0027s likelihood of establishing in labour within the next seven days?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transvaginal ultrasound","Partosure or Actim Partus testing","Vaginal examination","Ferning","Cardiotocography Score"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPreterm labour (PTL) is defined as regular uterine contractions with cervical change (dilatation or length of less than 20 mm on transvaginal ultrasound), or a positive Partosure or Actim Partus qualitative test in a woman between 20 and 36+6 weeks of gestation. It is divided into three categories:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eextremely preterm (less than 28 weeks)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Every preterm (28 to 32 weeks)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Emoderate to late preterm (32 to 36+6 weeks)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a history of previous preterm birth (PTB) at 35/40. Other history indicated risk factors include multiple dilation and curettage, previous cervical surgery, medical conditions such as diabetes, hypertension, renal disease, vaginal bleeding or infection and limited antenatal care. Obstetric factors that are associated with PTB include multiple pregnancy and polyhydramnios.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe initial assessment requires determination of the intensity and timing of contractions, a speculum examination and\u00a0high vaginal swab, urine microscopy, culture, and sensitivity\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eand a cardiotocography.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA vaginal examination is avoided\u00a0initially to allow for the\u003Cstrong\u003E Partosure or Actim Partus test\u003C/strong\u003E which is one of the three available tests used to determine the risk of this patient delivering in the next 7 days. These tests measures placental alpha microglobulin-1 (Partosure) or phosphorylated insulin-like growth factor binding protein-1 (Actim Partus).  \u00a0The overall sensitivity and specificity are 83.3% and 90.2% for Partosure and 83.3% and 76.2% for Actim Partus. The strength of these tests lies in the negative predictive values of 96.6-98%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce the Partosure swab has been taken, an ultrasound to confirm cephalic presentation is required. Pain relief is often given and if the contractions are continuing, nifedipine (20mg, PO, every 20mins for 3 doses, then TDS) is used as a tocolytic in the absence of bleeding. The QuiPP app (a clinical decision making tool) can be utilised in addition to further assess the risk of preterm birth and help determine clinical management, avoiding the risk of unnecessary treatments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the Partosure is positive, patients are admitted for observation and prescribed betamethasone (11.4mg IM, 2 doses) to decrease respiratory distress syndrome, hypoxic-ischemic encephalopathy (HIE) and necrotizing enterocolitis (NEC) as well as decrease NICU admissions in the event of PTB. If the contractions increase and labour progresses, urgent transfer to the birthing suite would be required. In an early preterm pregnancy (24-29+6/40), a magnesium infusion for neuroprotection is needed. It is important to know the limitations of the birthing unit- a positive fFN is often used to assist the decision to transfer a patient in PTL to a tertiary unit, depending on the gestational age limits that can be supported. Liaising with the neonatal/paediatric team to discuss the risks of PTB with the family as well as what to expect in terms of neonatal care/Nursery admission is also required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA negative Partosure has a reliable negative predictive value and if the tightenings have settled, it may be possible to manage the patient as an outpatient. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect:\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E transvaginal ultrasound \u003C/strong\u003Ein the setting of an open cervix will provide little additional information in the setting of regular contractions and is not always available. An ultrasound to confirm fetal presentation is important- if the fetus is presenting by the breech, different management may be needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no evidence to support a \u003Cstrong\u003Erepeat VE\u003C/strong\u003E unless the patient progresses into established labour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u00a0Ferning \u003C/strong\u003Eis a technique used to determine rupture of membranes, it is rarely used now and there is a higher reliance on an amnicator and clinical signs (pooling fluid, washed out\u00a0appearance, ongoing PV clear loss).\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003ECTG\u003C/strong\u003E will not be of use in predicting labour but will assess fetal wellbeing at this point in time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A negative Partosure/Actim partus has a reliable negative predictive value.","Preterm labour is defined as regular uterine contractions with cervical changes between 20 and 36+6 weeks of gestation.","Partosure/Actim Partus testing is useful in assessing the risk of preterm birth within the next seven days."],"references":["Varley-Campbell J, M\u00fajica-Mota R, Coelho H, et al. Three biomarker tests to help diagnose preterm labour: a systematic review and economic evaluation. Southampton (UK): NIHR Journals Library; 2019 Mar. (Health Technology Assessment, No. 23.13.) Chapter 2, Assessment of test accuracy. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539084/","Rouholamin S, Razavi M, Rezaeinejad M, Sepidarkish M. A diagnostic profile on the PartoSure test. Expert Rev Mol Diagn. 2020 Dec;20(12):1163-1170. doi: 10.1080/14737159.2020.1848549. Epub 2020 Dec 16. PMID: 33175636.","Melchor JC, Khalil A, Wing D, Schleussner E, Surbek D. Prediction of preterm delivery in symptomatic women using PAMG-1, fetal fibronectin and phIGFBP-1 tests: systematic review and meta-analysis. Ultrasound Obstet Gynecol. 2018 Oct;52(4):442-451. doi: 10.1002/uog.19119. Epub 2018 Sep 4. PMID: 29920825.","Antenatal Corticosteroid Clinical Practice Guidelines Panel.\u00a0Antenatal corticosteroids given to women prior to birth to improve fetal, infant, child and adult health: Clinical Practice Guidelines. 2015. Liggins Institute, The University of Auckland, Auckland. New Zealand. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Liggins-Institute-Antenatal-Corticosteroids.pdf","Melchor JC, Khalil A, Wing D, Schleussner E, Surbek D. Prediction of preterm delivery in symptomatic women using PAMG-1, fetal fibronectin and phIGFBP-1 tests: systematic review and meta-analysis.\u00a0Ultrasound Obstet Gynecol. 2018;52(4):442\u2010451. doi:10.1002/uog.19119 Availble from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29920825/","National Collaborating Centre for Women\u0027s and Children\u0027s Health (UK). Preterm Labour and Birth. London: National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (UK); 2015 Nov. PMID: 26632624. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26632624/","Quipp app website. [Internet]. https://quipp.org. Accessed Feb 2025. Available from: https://quipp.org"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"101490"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/119711/itemRevision","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/119711/relationships/itemRevision"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"974"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/119711/question","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/119711/relationships/question"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/119711/stemMedia","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/119711/relationships/stemMedia"}},"explanationMedia":{"data":[],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/119711/explanationMedia","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/119711/relationships/expla